Intel Concerns
--------------

From Reuters ( https://www.reuters.com/technology/intel-board-member-quit-a=
fter-differences-over-chipmakers-revival-plan-2024-08-27/ ) :

The sudden resignation of a high-profile Intel board member came after diff=
erences with CEO Pat Gelsinger and other directors over what the director c=
onsidered the U.S. company=E2=80=99s bloated workforce, risk-averse culture=
 and lagging artificial intelligence strategy, according to three sources f=
amiliar with the matter.

Lip-Bu Tan, a semiconductor industry veteran, had said he was leaving the b=
oard because of a personal decision to =E2=80=9Creprioritize various commit=
ments=E2=80=9D and that he remained =E2=80=9Csupportive of the company and =
its important work,=E2=80=9D in a regulatory filing on Thursday. The former=
 CEO of chip-software company Cadence Design joined Intel=E2=80=99s board t=
wo years ago as part of a plan to restore Intel=E2=80=99s place as the lead=
ing global chipmaker. The board expanded Tan=E2=80=99s responsibilities in =
October 2023, authorizing him to oversee manufacturing operations.

Over time, Tan grew frustrated by the company=E2=80=99s large workforce, it=
s approach to contract manufacturing and Intel=E2=80=99s risk-averse and bu=
reaucratic culture, according to the sources, who were not authorized to sp=
eak publicly. The circumstances around Tan=E2=80=99s exit have not previous=
ly been reported. The departure of the industry veteran, who is well-regard=
ed by investors, over Intel=E2=80=99s strategy illustrates the uncertainty =
of its turnaround efforts.

Board-level changes aren=E2=80=99t generally something I cover on Strateche=
ry, but I wanted to touch on this one for a few reasons.

First off, I never really took a close look at Intel=E2=80=99s board before=
, but it doesn=E2=80=99t strike me as being very strong; with Tan=E2=80=99s=
 exit (and excluding CEO Pat Gelsinger) there are three academics, three pe=
ople from the finance industry (one VC), two from non-tech businesses, two =
from the tech industry, and one Intel veteran from sales. There isn=E2=80=
=99t anyone with deep knowledge or expertise in actual silicon manufacturin=
g. I guess this shouldn=E2=80=99t be a surprise: one of the key ingredients=
 for a company that has so consistently screwed up, as Intel has over the l=
ast two decades, is surely a board that is not doing its job, or worse, doe=
sn=E2=80=99t seem equipped to understand precisely what is going wrong and =
thus needs to be fixed.

Tan was someone who could change that: one of the essential parts of the fo=
undry model is the software that is used to design chips, and Tan was the C=
EO and then executive-chairman of Cadence, one of the leaders in that space=
; no wonder he was put in charge of overseeing Intel=E2=80=99s manufacturin=
g operations and the development of its foundry model last fall. For him to=
 suddenly leave is a major red flag and ought to shine a light on just how =
lacking the current board is.

Secondly, with regards to those grievances, it seems clear that Tan has a p=
oint: I was too gentle last week ( https://stratechery.com/2024/intel-earni=
ngs-intels-nadir/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZX=
