The more fundamental issue is that a foundry is, as I wrote, a customer ser=
vice organization: an entity like TSMC adapts to customers=E2=80=99 designs=
, not the other way around. They use industry standard design software. The=
y have extensive libraries of IP that make designing a chip more akin to as=
sembling a collection of Lego blocks. They ship when they say they will shi=
p, and they run the fab for which a chip was designed forever.

Intel did none of these things, and had a mentality and culture that ran in=
 the exact opposite direction: in a foundry, manufacturing is not king but =
a servant; customer sales is not about =E2=80=9Ctake-it-or-leave-it=E2=80=
=9D but =E2=80=9Clet us help you solve your problem.=E2=80=9D I was =E2=80=
=94 and frankly, remain =E2=80=94 dubious about Intel=E2=80=99s ability to =
create that sort of culture internally, which is why I advocated for an acq=
uisition, first of Global Foundries, and then of Tower. Thanks to its decad=
e delay Intel didn=E2=80=99t have time to learn how to serve customers: it =
had rapidly obsoleting fabs that needed to be filled as soon as possible, i=
f the company ever had hope of making enough cash to fund its push back to =
the leading edge.

Unfortunately China blocked the acquisition of Tower, in what I suspect was=
 retaliation for U.S. restrictions on China ( https://stratechery.com/2022/=
china-chip-ban-clarifications-nvidias-a800-china-intel-and-tower/?access_to=
ken=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsI=
