Gfc-bzdfIR7R8rp5mQ2o_TKi30xi44ltHMZFBXZTGbiirRojKrOK_G1K9GJcEGxncndANconVLc=
ri8bBR015DKQiNUUXPIo7gNBZvYUPetkw ).

This report does seem to confirm my worst fears: Intel=E2=80=99s culture ju=
st isn=E2=80=99t suited to serving others. Of course that could be confirma=
tion bias, but that actually highlights another issue =E2=80=94 the lack of=
 disconfirming evidence. Specifically, while I noted that Gelsinger=E2=80=
=99s tenure shouldn=E2=80=99t be fully judged until the 18A node, it is get=
ting to be a big problem that there aren=E2=80=99t yet any meaningful custo=
mer announcements about companies using that node for anything beyond exper=
iments. Intel says it plans to start production next year, which means it i=
s getting close to put-up-or-shut-up time as far as external customers are =
concerned.

That, finally, leads me to the biggest point I under-emphasized last week: =
the fact that Intel had a massive margin miss because of chips it made on i=
ts latest process is a massive red flag. Yes, it=E2=80=99s true that ramps =
are expensive, and that said node was a stepping stone on the way to 18A; a=
t the same time, Intel didn=E2=80=99t just miss the street=E2=80=99s margin=
 predictions, but their own predictions =E2=80=94 that=E2=80=99s partly why=
 the stock was crushed so badly, because the miss was unexpected.

That, by extension, suggests that (1) Intel doesn=E2=80=99t have a hold on =
costs for its newest processes and (2) the company can=E2=80=99t effectivel=
y predict costs for its processes. How can a company that drastically misse=
s its internal cost projections successfully sell its services to outside c=
ompanies who, as an alternative, can simply go to a company in TSMC who is =
far more reliable and easier to work with and, critically, delivers at pric=
es it promises ahead of time?

I do still stand by my take that Gelsinger deserves a chance to deliver on =
18A, and that the broader strategy is correct. There is, however, a concern=
ing trend that is emerging: Gelsinger is relentlessly positive and optimist=
ic, but, to invoke his mentor Andy Grove ( https://stratechery.com/2016/and=
y-grove-and-the-iphone-se/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0c=
mF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGV=
yeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ij=
